Notes:

 

Irrelevant data through API:

 

There will be a number of cases in which we may send you data that is not applicable in the context of other data.  For example, with respect to data buffering, we may send you the value kRemote for destination (as opposed to kLocal).  In this case, the mode (linear or circular) is meaningless - that choice is only given to the end user if they want to buffer locally.  However, we're implementing these rules in terms of layers in the HTML code, so even though the linear/circular mode is invisible to the user when they select "Remote", linear or circular is still passed to the middleware, and we don't want to duplicate logic there, so we'll just pass on all the data to you.  You'll have to decide whether or not certain data is applicable.  In this case, you'd ignore the linear/circular datum.  No error return or other notification, just ignore it.  In the future, should that option be made available even for remote data logging, then we'd open it up on the front end and you'd change the rules on the backend - we won't have to do anything to the middleware logic.

 

When looking at the GuiFieldSpec, you can identify wherever this kind of thing may happen: wherever you see "Selected item impacts fields below" in the notes column, you're looking at a page that contains some fields which we might pass on despite their meaninglessness.

 

 

Wizard Pages - High-level View

The “Wizard” mode is for administrators only.  When an administrator logs on, s/he enters the site at step 1 of the wizard.  S/he may push the “Expert” button at the bottom left of the page to toggle to “Normal” mode (known as “Expert” mode when compared to the “Wizard”, for an admin).

 

Step 1: Network Settings

Step 2: CAS Profile Settings

Step 3: Access

Step 4: Port Access

Step 5: Data Buffering

Step 6: System Log

Normal Pages - High-level View

The “Normal” mode is for administrators and regular users.  Administrators may push the “Wizard” button at the bottom left of the page to toggle to “Wizard” mode.  After login, non-admin users enter the site at the Applications | Connect page, where s/he can use the CLI to connect to a system (most common activity for a non-admin user).  When they come from the “Wizard” mode, admin users enter the “Normal” mode at the Applications | Ports page, where s/he can configure ports (most common activity for admin user).  The two bold items under Terminal identify the common non-admin user “applications”.

 

The first level of indentation (in fact, no indentation) indicates the high-level options shown at the top of the screen.  The second level of indentation indicates the left-hand menu, which is different for each top-level option.  The third level of indentation usually indicates tabs within the page, but every third indentation level is labeled for clarification.  Black items are accessible by all, blue items are accessible only by administrators.

Up to three icon-buttons could be placed in cells in this column, as described below.

 

N/A

Icon-button

(Light bulb on / Light bulb off)

This icon-button portrays the power status of the outlet: on or off.  It is always drawn (in one of the two specified states), and is always first in the cell. The icon-button can be pushed (thus toggling the state) iff the outlet is “unlocked” (see next field).

(Immediate API call.  When an outlet is turned on, all status must be re-retrieved, because the outlet may automatically go into “locked” state (see next field).)

 

N/A

Icon-button

(Locked / Unlocked)

This icon-button portrays the locked status of the outlet: locked or unlocked.  It is always drawn (in one of the two specified states), and is always second in the cell.  The icon-button can be pushed (thus toggling the state).  When “locked”, the light-bulb icon-button should be disabled, but should show the correct state.

(Immediate API call.)

 

N/A

Icon-button

(Cycle)

This icon-button is only a button (no status); It is grayed/disabled if the outlet is “off”, but can be pushed if the outlet is “on”, to “cycle” the outlet (flip it off then on again, effectively).

(Immediate API call; items for on, off, and cycle.)
